'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_2"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Syntax"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eSyntax\x3c/h2\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3enew Boolean(value)\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3c/div\x3e','\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_3"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Parameters"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eParameters\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cdl\x3e \x3cdt\x3e\x3ccode\x3evalue\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/dt\x3e \x3cdd\x3eThe initial value of the \x3ccode\x3eBoolean\x3c/code\x3e object.\x3c/dd\x3e\n\x3c/dl\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e',
'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_4"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Description"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eDescription\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThe value passed as the first parameter is converted to a boolean value, if necessary. If value is omitted or is 0, -0, null, false, \x3ccode\x3eNaN\x3c/code\x3e, undefined, or the empty string (\x26quot;\x26quot;), the object has an initial value of false. All other values, including any object or the string \x3ccode\x3e\x26quot;false\x26quot;\x3c/code\x3e, create an object with an initial value of true.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eDo not confuse the primitive Boolean values true and false with the true and false values of the Boolean object.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eAny object whose value is not \x3ccode\x3eundefined\x3c/code\x3e or \x3ccode\x3enull\x3c/code\x3e, including a Boolean object whose value is false, evaluates to true when passed to a conditional statement. For example, the condition in the following if statement evaluates to true:\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3ex \x3d new Boolean(false);\nif (x) {\n  // . . . this code is executed\n}\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eThis behavior does not apply to Boolean primitives. For example, the condition in the following if statement evaluates to \x3ccode\x3efalse\x3c/code\x3e:\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3ex \x3d false;\nif (x) {\n  // . . . this code is not executed\n}\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eDo not use a \x3ccode\x3eBoolean\x3c/code\x3e object to convert a non-boolean value to a boolean value. Instead, use Boolean as a function to perform this task:\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3ex \x3d Boolean(expression);     // preferred\nx \x3d new Boolean(expression); // don\'t use\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eIf you specify any object, including a Boolean object whose value is false, as the initial value of a Boolean object, the new Boolean object has a value of true.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3emyFalse \x3d new Boolean(false);   // initial value of false\ng \x3d new Boolean(myFalse);       // initial value of true\nmyString \x3d new String(\x26quot;Hello\x26quot;); // string object\ns \x3d new Boolean(myString);      // initial value of true\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eDo not use a Boolean object in place of a Boolean primitive.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e',
