'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_11"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Examples"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eExamples\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_12"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Example:_Using_a_regular_expression_to_change_data_format"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3eExample: Using a regular expression to change data format\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThe following script uses the \x3ca title \x3d "en/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/replace" rel \x3d "internal" href \x3d "https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/replace"\x3ereplace\x3c/a\x3e method inherited by the \x3ca title \x3d "en/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String" rel \x3d "internal" href \x3d "https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String"\x3eString\x3c/a\x3e instance to match a name in the format \x3cem\x3efirst last\x3c/em\x3e and output it in the format \x3cem\x3elast\x3c/em\x3e, \x3cem\x3efirst\x3c/em\x3e. In the replacement text, the script uses \x3ccode\x3e$1\x3c/code\x3e and \x3ccode\x3e$2\x3c/code\x3e to indicate the results of the corresponding matching parentheses in the regular expression pattern.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3evar re \x3d /(\\w+)\\s(\\w+)/;\nvar str \x3d \x26quot;John Smith\x26quot;;\nvar newstr \x3d str.replace(re, \x26quot;$2, $1\x26quot;);\nprint(newstr);\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eThis displays \x26quot;Smith, John\x26quot;.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_13"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Example:_Using_a_regular_expression_with_the_.22sticky.22_flag"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3eExample: Using a regular expression with the \x26quot;sticky\x26quot; flag\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThis example demonstrates how one could use the sticky flag on regular expressions to match individual lines of multiline input.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3evar text \x3d \x26quot;First line\\nsecond line\x26quot;;\nvar regex \x3d /(\\S+) line\\n?/y;\n\nvar match \x3d regex.exec(text);\nprint(match[1]);  // prints \x26quot;First\x26quot;\nprint(regex.lastIndex); // prints 11\n\nvar match2 \x3d regex.exec(text);\nprint(match2[1]); // prints \x26quot;Second\x26quot;\nprint(regex.lastIndex); // prints \x26quot;22\x26quot;\n\nvar match3 \x3d regex.exec(text);\nprint(match3 \x3d\x3d\x3d null); // prints \x26quot;true\x26quot;\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eOne can test at run-time whether the sticky flag is supported, using \x3ccode\x3etry\x26nbsp;{\x26nbsp;\x26hellip;\x26nbsp;} catch\x26nbsp;{\x26nbsp;\x26hellip;\x26nbsp;}\x3c/code\x3e. For this, either an \x3ccode\x3eeval(\x26hellip;)\x3c/code\x3e expression or the \x3ccode\x3eRegExp(\x3cvar\x3eregex-string\x3c/var\x3e,\x26nbsp;\x3cvar\x3eflags-string\x3c/var\x3e)\x3c/code\x3e syntax must be used (since the \x3ccode\x3e/\x3cvar\x3eregex\x3c/var\x3e/\x3cvar\x3eflags\x3c/var\x3e\x3c/code\x3e notation is processed at compile-time, so throws an exception before the \x3ccode\x3ecatch\x3c/code\x3e block is encountered). For example:\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3evar supports_sticky;\ntry { RegExp(\'\',\'y\'); supports_sticky \x3d true; }\ncatch(e) { supports_sticky \x3d false; }\nalert(supports_sticky); // alerts \x26quot;false\x26quot; in Firefox 2, \x26quot;true\x26quot; in Firefox 3+\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3c/div\x3e\x3c/div\x3e',
