'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_4"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Description"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eDescription\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cp\x3e\x3ccode\x3elet\x3c/code\x3e allows you to declare variables, limiting its scope to the block, statement, or expression on which is used. This is unlike the \x3ca title \x3d "en/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/var" rel \x3d "internal" href \x3d "https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/var"\x3e\x3ccode\x3evar\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/a\x3e keyword, which defines a variable globally, or local to an entire function regardless of block scope.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e',
'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_5"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Examples"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eExamples\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eA \x3cem\x3elet expression\x3c/em\x3e limit the scope of the variable declared only in that expression.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3evar a \x3d 5;\nlet(a \x3d 6) alert(a); // 6\nalert(a); // 5\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3e\x26nbsp;Used inside a block, \x3cem\x3elet\x3c/em\x3e limits the variable\'s scope to that block. Note the difference between \x3cem\x3evar \x3c/em\x3ewhich its scope is inside the function where is declared\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3evar a \x3d 5;\nvar b \x3d 10;\nif (a \x3d\x3d\x3d 5) {\n  let a \x3d 4; // The scope is inside the if-block\n  var b \x3d 1; // The scope is inside the function\n\n  0 \x26\x26 console.log(a);  // 4\n  0 \x26\x26 console.log(b);  // 1\n} \n0 \x26\x26 console.log(a); // 5\n0 \x26\x26 console.log(b); // 1\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eYou can use the \x3cem\x3elet\x3c/em\x3e keyword to bind variables locally in the scope of for loops instead of using a global variable (defined using \x3cem\x3evar\x3c/em\x3e) for that.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3efor (let i \x3d 0; i\x26lt;10; i++) {\n  alert(i); // 1, 2, 3, 4 ... 9\n}\n\nalert(i); // i is not defined\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3c/div\x3e',
