'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_4"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Description"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eDescription\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThe \x3ccode\x3einstanceof\x3c/code\x3e operator tests presence of \x3ccode\x3econstructor.prototype\x3c/code\x3e in \x3ccode\x3eobject\x3c/code\x3e prototype chain.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3efunction C(){} // defining a constructor\nfunction D(){} // defining another constructor\n\nvar o \x3d new C();\no instanceof C; // true, because: Object.getPrototypeOf(o) \x3d\x3d\x3d C.prototype\no instanceof D; // false, because D.prototype is nowhere in o\'s prototype chain\no instanceof Object; // true, because:\nC.prototype instanceof Object // true\n\nC.prototype \x3d {};\nvar o2 \x3d new C();\no2 instanceof C; // true\no instanceof C; // false, because C.prototype is nowhere in o\'s prototype chain anymore\n\nD.prototype \x3d Object.getPrototypeOf(o);\no instanceof D; // true\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eNote that if the value of an \x3ccode\x3einstanceof\x3c/code\x3e test can change based on changes to the \x3ccode\x3eprototype\x3c/code\x3e property of constructors, it cannot be changed by changing an object prototype, because changing an object prototype is not possible in standard ECMAScript. It is however possible using the non-standard \x3ccode\x3e__proto__\x3c/code\x3e pseudo-property.\x3c/p\x3e \x3cdiv id \x3d "section_5"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "instanceof_and_multiple_context_(e.g._frames_or_windows)"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3e\x3ccode\x3einstanceof\x3c/code\x3e and multiple context (e.g. frames or windows)\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eDifferent scope have different execution environments. This means that they have different built-ins (different global object, different constructors, etc.). This may result in unexpected results. For instance, if \x3ccode\x3eArray2\x3c/code\x3e is the \x3ccode\x3eArray\x3c/code\x3e constructor of another context, \x3ccode\x3e[] instanceof Array2\x3c/code\x3e will return \x3ccode\x3efalse\x3c/code\x3e, because \x3ccode\x3eArray.prototype !\x3d\x3d Array2.prototype\x3c/code\x3e and arrays inherit from the former.\x3c/p\x3e\x3c/div\x3e\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_6"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Mozilla_developers"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3eMozilla developers\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eIn code using XPCOM \x3ccode\x3einstanceof\x3c/code\x3e has special effect: \x3ccode\x3eobj instanceof \x3c/code\x3e\x3cem\x3e\x3ccode\x3expcomInterface\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/em\x3e (e.g. \x3ccode\x3eComponents.interfaces.nsIFile\x3c/code\x3e) calls \x3ccode\x3eobj.QueryInterface(\x3cem\x3expcomInterface\x3c/em\x3e)\x3c/code\x3e and returns \x3ccode\x3etrue\x3c/code\x3e if QueryInterface succeeded. A side effect of such call is that you can use \x3cem\x3e\x3ccode\x3expcomInterface\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/em\x3e\'s properties on \x3ccode\x3eobj\x3c/code\x3e after a successful \x3ccode\x3einstanceof\x3c/code\x3e test.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eUnlike standard JavaScript globals, the test \x3ccode\x3eobj instanceof xpcomInterface \x3c/code\x3eworks as expected even if \x3ccode\x3eobj\x3c/code\x3e is from a different scope.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e\x3c/div\x3e',
