'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_2"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Syntax"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3eSyntax\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3e\x3ccode\x3e\x3cem\x3eobject\x3c/em\x3e.toString()\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e','\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_3"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Description"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3eDescription\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eEvery object has a \x3ccode\x3etoString()\x3c/code\x3e method that is automatically called when the object is to be represented as a text value or when an object is referred to in a manner in which a string is expected. By default, the \x3ccode\x3etoString()\x3c/code\x3e method is inherited by every object descended from \x3ccode\x3eObject\x3c/code\x3e. If this method is not overridden in a custom object, \x3ccode\x3etoString()\x3c/code\x3e returns \x26quot;[object \x3cem\x3etype\x3c/em\x3e]\x26quot;, where \x3ccode\x3e\x3cem\x3etype\x3c/em\x3e\x3c/code\x3e is the object type. The following code illustrates this:\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cpre class \x3d "eval"\x3e\nvar o \x3d new Object();\no.toString();           // returns [object Object]\n\x3c/pre\x3e\n\x3cdiv class \x3d "note"\x3eStarting in JavaScript 1.8.5 \x3ccode\x3etoString()\x3c/code\x3e called on \x3ccode\x3enull\x3c/code\x3e returns \x3ccode\x3e[object \x3cem\x3eNull\x3c/em\x3e]\x3c/code\x3e, and \x3ccode\x3eundefined\x3c/code\x3e returns \x3ccode\x3e[object \x3cem\x3eUndefined\x3c/em\x3e]\x3c/code\x3e, as defined in the 5th Edition of ECMAScript and a subsequent Errata. See \x3ca title \x3d "en/JavaScript/Reference/Global Objects/Object/toString#Using toString to detect object type" rel \x3d "internal" href \x3d "https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/toString#Using_toString_to_detect_object_type"\x3eUsing toString to detect object type\x3c/a\x3e.\x3c/div\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e',
