'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_2"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Syntax"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eSyntax\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cp\x3e\x3ccode\x3e\x3cem\x3eprototype\x3c/em\x3e.isPrototypeOf(\x3cem\x3eobject\x3c/em\x3e)\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e','\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_3"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Parameters"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eParameters\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cdl\x3e \x3cdt\x3eprototype\x3c/dt\x3e \x3cdd\x3e\x26nbsp; an object to be tested against each link in the prototype chain of the \x3cstrong\x3eobject\x3c/strong\x3e\x26nbsp; argument\x3c/dd\x3e\n\x3c/dl\x3e\n\x3cp\x3e\x3cdiv class \x3d "note"\x3e\x3cstrong\x3eNote:\x3c/strong\x3e\x26nbsp;\x3ccode\x3eisPrototypeOf\x3c/code\x3e differs from \x3ca rel \x3d "internal" href \x3d "https://developer.mozilla.org/en/Core_JavaScript_1.5_Reference/Operators/Special_Operators/instanceof_Operator" title \x3d "en/Core_JavaScript_1.5_Reference/Operators/Special_Operators/instanceof_Operator"\x3einstanceof operator\x3c/a\x3e. In the expression \x3ccode\x3eobject instanceof AFunction\x3c/code\x3e, the \x3ccode\x3eobject\x3c/code\x3e prototype chain is checked against \x3ccode\x3eAFunction.prototype\x3c/code\x3e, not against \x3ccode\x3eAFunction\x3c/code\x3e itself\x3c/div\x3e\n\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cdl\x3e \x3cdt\x3eobject\x3c/dt\x3e \x3cdd\x3ethe object whose prototype chain will be searched\x3c/dd\x3e\n\x3c/dl\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e',
'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_4"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Description"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eDescription\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cp\x3e\x3ccode\x3eisPrototypeOf\x3c/code\x3e allows you to check whether or not an object exists within another object\'s prototype chain.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eFor example, consider the following prototype chain:\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cpre class \x3d "eval"\x3efunction Fee() {\n  // . . .\n}\n\nfunction Fi() {\n  // . . .\n}\nFi.prototype \x3d new Fee();\n\nfunction Fo() {\n  // . . .\n}\nFo.prototype \x3d new Fi();\n\nfunction Fum() {\n  // . . .\n}\nFum.prototype \x3d new Fo();\n\x3c/pre\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eLater on down the road, if you instantiate \x3ccode\x3eFum\x3c/code\x3e and need to check if \x3ccode\x3eFi\x3c/code\x3e\'s prototype exists within the \x3ccode\x3eFum\x3c/code\x3e prototype chain, you could do this:\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cpre class \x3d "eval"\x3evar fum \x3d new Fum();\n. . .\n\nif (Fi.prototype.isPrototypeOf(fum)) {\n  // do something safe\n}\n\x3c/pre\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThis, along with the \x3ccode\x3einstanceof\x3c/code\x3e operator particularly comes in handy if you have code that can only function when dealing with objects descended from a specific prototype chain, e.g., to guarantee that certain methods or properties will be present on that object.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e',
