'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_4"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Description"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3eDescription\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3e\x3ccode\x3ereduceRight\x3c/code\x3e executes the callback function once for each element present in the array, excluding holes in the array, receiving four arguments: the initial value (or value from the previous callback call), the value of the current element, the current index, and the array over which iteration is occurring.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThe call to the reduceRight \x3ccode\x3ecallback\x3c/code\x3e would look something like this:\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cpre class \x3d "eval"\x3earray.reduceRight(function(previousValue, currentValue, index, array) {\n    // ...\n});\n\x3c/pre\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThe first time the function is called, the \x3ccode\x3epreviousValue\x3c/code\x3e and \x3ccode\x3ecurrentValue\x3c/code\x3e can be one of two values. If an \x3ccode\x3einitialValue\x3c/code\x3e was provided in the call to \x3ccode\x3ereduceRight\x3c/code\x3e, then \x3ccode\x3epreviousValue\x3c/code\x3e will be equal to \x3ccode\x3einitialValue\x3c/code\x3e and \x3ccode\x3ecurrentValue\x3c/code\x3e will be equal to the last value in the array. If no \x3ccode\x3einitialValue\x3c/code\x3e was provided, then \x3ccode\x3epreviousValue\x3c/code\x3e will be equal to the last value in the array and \x3ccode\x3ecurrentValue\x3c/code\x3e will be equal to the second-to-last value.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eSome example run-throughs of the function would look like this:\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3e[0, 1, 2, 3, 4].reduceRight(function(previousValue, currentValue, index, array) {\n    return previousValue + currentValue;\n});\n\n// First call\npreviousValue \x3d 4, currentValue \x3d 3, index \x3d 3\n\n// Second call\npreviousValue \x3d 7, currentValue \x3d 2, index \x3d 2\n\n// Third call\npreviousValue \x3d 9, currentValue \x3d 1, index \x3d 1\n\n// Fourth call\npreviousValue \x3d 10, currentValue \x3d 0, index \x3d 0\n\n// array is always the object [0,1,2,3,4] upon which reduceRight was called\n\n// Return Value: 10\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eAnd if you were to provide an \x3ccode\x3einitialValue\x3c/code\x3e, the result would look like this:\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3e[0, 1, 2, 3, 4].reduceRight(function(previousValue, currentValue, index, array) {\n    return previousValue + currentValue;\n}, 10);\n\n// First call\npreviousValue \x3d 10, currentValue \x3d 4, index \x3d 4\n\n// Second call\npreviousValue \x3d 14, currentValue \x3d 3, index \x3d 3\n\n// Third call\npreviousValue \x3d 17, currentValue \x3d 2, index \x3d 2\n\n// Fourth call\npreviousValue \x3d 19, currentValue \x3d 1, index \x3d 1\n\n// Fifth call\npreviousValue \x3d 20, currentValue \x3d 0, index \x3d 0\n\n// array is always the object [0,1,2,3,4] upon which reduceRight was called\n\n// Return Value: 20\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3c/div\x3e',
