'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_2"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Syntax"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eSyntax\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cp\x3e\x3ccode\x3e\x3cem\x3efun\x3c/em\x3e.call(\x3cem\x3ethisArg\x3c/em\x3e[, \x3cem\x3earg1\x3c/em\x3e[, \x3cem\x3earg2\x3c/em\x3e[, ...]]])\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e','\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_3"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Parameters"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 style \x3d "position: static; z-index: auto; " class \x3d "editable"\x3eParameters\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cdl\x3e \x3cdt\x3e\x3ccode\x3ethisArg\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/dt\x3e \x3cdd\x3eThe value of \x3ccode\x3ethis\x3c/code\x3e provided for the call to\x26nbsp;\x3cem\x3e\x3ccode\x3efun\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/em\x3e. \x26nbsp;Note that this may not be the actual value seen by the method: if the method is a function in \x3ca title \x3d "en/JavaScript/Strict mode" rel \x3d "internal" href \x3d "https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Reference/Functions_and_function_scope/Strict_mode"\x3enon-strict mode\x3c/a\x3e code, \x3ccode\x3enull\x3c/code\x3e and \x3ccode\x3eundefined\x3c/code\x3e will be replaced with the global object, and primitive values will be boxed.\x3c/dd\x3e\n\x3c/dl\x3e\n\x3cdl\x3e \x3cdt\x3e\x3ccode\x3earg1, arg2, ...\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/dt\x3e \x3cdd\x3eArguments for the object.\x3c/dd\x3e\n\x3c/dl\x3e\x3c/div\x3e',
'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_4"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Description"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d "editable"\x3eDescription\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eYou can assign a different \x3ccode\x3ethis\x3c/code\x3e object when calling an existing function. \x3ccode\x3ethis\x3c/code\x3e refers to the current object, the calling object.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eWith \x3ccode\x3ecall\x3c/code\x3e, you can write a method once and then inherit it in another object, without having to rewrite the method for the new object.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e',
"\x3cdiv id \x3d \"section_5\"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d \"Examples\"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch2 class \x3d \"editable\"\x3eExamples\x3c/h2\x3e\n\x3cdiv id \x3d \"section_6\"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d \"Using_call_to_chain_constructors_for_an_object\"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d \"editable\"\x3eUsing \x3ccode\x3ecall\x3c/code\x3e to chain constructors for an object\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eYou can use \x3ccode\x3ecall\x3c/code\x3e to chain constructors for an object, similar to Java.\x26nbsp;In the following example, the constructor for the\x26nbsp;\x3ccode\x3eProduct\x3c/code\x3e\x26nbsp;object is defined with two parameters, \x3ccode\x3ename\x3c/code\x3e\x26nbsp;and\x26nbsp;\x3ccode\x3evalue\x3c/code\x3e. Two other functions\x26nbsp;\x3ccode\x3eFood\x3c/code\x3e\x26nbsp;and\x26nbsp;\x3ccode\x3eToy\x3c/code\x3e\x26nbsp;invoke\x26nbsp;\x3ccode\x3eProduct\x3c/code\x3e\x26nbsp;passing\x26nbsp;\x3ccode\x3ethis\x3c/code\x3e\x26nbsp;and\x26nbsp;\x3ccode\x3ename\x3c/code\x3e\x26nbsp;and\x26nbsp;\x3ccode\x3evalue\x3c/code\x3e. Product initializes the properties name and price, both specialized functions define the category.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d \"code\" class \x3d \"js\"\x3efunction Product(name, price) {\n  this.name \x3d name;\n  this.price \x3d price;\n\n  if (price \x26lt; 0)\n    throw RangeError('Cannot create product \x26quot;' + name + '\x26quot; with a negative price');\n  return this;\n}\n\nfunction Food(name, price) {\n  Product.call(this, name, price);\n  this.category \x3d 'food';\n}\nFood.prototype \x3d new Product();\n\nfunction Toy(name, price) {\n  Product.call(this, name, price);\n  this.category \x3d 'toy';\n}\nToy.prototype \x3d new Product();\n\nvar cheese \x3d new Food('feta', 5);\nvar fun \x3d new Toy('robot', 40);\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3c/div\x3e\x3cdiv id \x3d \"section_7\"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d \"Using_call_to_invoke_an_anonymous_function\"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d \"editable\"\x3eUsing \x3ccode\x3ecall\x3c/code\x3e to invoke an anonymous function\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eIn this purely constructed example, we create anonymous function and use \x3ccode\x3ecall\x3c/code\x3e to invoke it on every object in an array. The main purpose of the anonymous function here is to add a print function to every object, which is able to print the right index of the object in the array. Passing the object as \x3ccode\x3ethis\x3c/code\x3e value was not strictly necessary, but is done for explanatory purpose.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d \"code\" class \x3d \"js\"\x3evar animals \x3d [\n  {species: 'Lion', name: 'King'},\n  {species: 'Whale', name: 'Fail'}\n];\n\nfor (var i \x3d 0; i \x26lt; animals.length; i++) {\n  (function (i) { \n    this.print \x3d function () { \n      0 \x26\x26 console.log('#' + i  + ' ' + this.species + ': ' + this.name); \n    } \n  }).call(animals[i], i);\n}\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3c/div\x3e\x3c/div\x3e",
