'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_4"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Description"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3eDescription\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThe \x3ccode\x3esplit\x3c/code\x3e method returns the new array.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eWhen found, \x3ccode\x3eseparator\x3c/code\x3e is removed from the string and the substrings are returned in an array. If \x3ccode\x3eseparator\x3c/code\x3e is omitted, the array contains one element consisting of the entire string.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eIf \x3ccode\x3eseparator\x3c/code\x3e is a regular expression that contains capturing parentheses, then each time separator is matched the results (including any undefined results) of the capturing parentheses are spliced into the output array. However, not all browsers support this capability.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3e\x3cdiv class \x3d "note"\x3e\x3cstrong\x3eNote:\x3c/strong\x3e\x26nbsp;When the string is empty, \x3ccode\x3esplit\x3c/code\x3e returns an array containing one empty string, rather than an empty array.\x3c/div\x3e\n\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e',
'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_5"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Examples"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3eExamples\x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_6"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Example:_Using_split"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch4 class \x3d "editable"\x3eExample: Using \x3ccode\x3esplit\x3c/code\x3e\x3c/h4\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThe following example defines a function that splits a string into an array of strings using the specified separator. After splitting the string, the function displays messages indicating the original string (before the split), the separator used, the number of elements in the array, and the individual array elements.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3efunction splitString(stringToSplit,separator)\n{\n  var arrayOfStrings \x3d stringToSplit.split(separator);\n  print(\'The original string is: \x26quot;\' + stringToSplit + \'\x26quot;\');\n  print(\'The separator is: \x26quot;\' + separator + \'\x26quot;\');\n  print(\x26quot;The array has \x26quot; + arrayOfStrings.length + \x26quot; elements: \x26quot;);\n\n  for (var i\x3d0; i \x26lt; arrayOfStrings.length; i++)\n    print(arrayOfStrings[i] + \x26quot; / \x26quot;);\n}\n\nvar tempestString \x3d \x26quot;Oh brave new world that has such people in it.\x26quot;;\nvar monthString \x3d \x26quot;Jan,Feb,Mar,Apr,May,Jun,Jul,Aug,Sep,Oct,Nov,Dec\x26quot;;\n\nvar space \x3d \x26quot; \x26quot;;\nvar comma \x3d \x26quot;,\x26quot;;\n\nsplitString(tempestString, space);\nsplitString(tempestString);\nsplitString(monthString, comma);\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eThis example produces the following output:\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cpre class \x3d "eval"\x3eThe original string is: \x26quot;Oh brave new world that has such people in it.\x26quot;\nThe separator is: \x26quot; \x26quot;\nThe array has 10 elements: Oh / brave / new / world / that / has / such / people / in / it. /\n\nThe original string is: \x26quot;Oh brave new world that has such people in it.\x26quot;\nThe separator is: \x26quot;undefined\x26quot;\nThe array has 1 elements: Oh brave new world that has such people in it. /\n\nThe original string is: \x26quot;Jan,Feb,Mar,Apr,May,Jun,Jul,Aug,Sep,Oct,Nov,Dec\x26quot;\nThe separator is: \x26quot;,\x26quot;\nThe array has 12 elements: Jan / Feb / Mar / Apr / May / Jun / Jul / Aug / Sep / Oct / Nov / Dec /\n\x3c/pre\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_7"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Example:_Removing_spaces_from_a_string"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch4 class \x3d "editable"\x3eExample: Removing spaces from a string\x3c/h4\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eIn the following example, \x3ccode\x3esplit\x3c/code\x3e looks for 0 or more spaces followed by a semicolon followed by 0 or more spaces and, when found, removes the spaces from the string. \x3ccode\x3enameList\x3c/code\x3e is the array returned as a result of \x3ccode\x3esplit\x3c/code\x3e.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3evar names \x3d \x26quot;Harry Trump ;Fred Barney; Helen Rigby ; Bill Abel ;Chris Hand \x26quot;;\nprint(names);\nvar re \x3d /\\s*;\\s*/;\nvar nameList \x3d names.split(re);\nprint(nameList);\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eThis prints two lines; the first line prints the original string, and the second line prints the resulting array.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cpre class \x3d "eval"\x3eHarry Trump\x26nbsp;;Fred Barney; Helen Rigby\x26nbsp;; Bill Abel\x26nbsp;;Chris Hand\nHarry Trump,Fred Barney,Helen Rigby,Bill Abel,Chris Hand\n\x3c/pre\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_8"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Example:_Returning_a_limited_number_of_splits"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch4 class \x3d "editable"\x3eExample: Returning a limited number of splits\x3c/h4\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eIn the following example, \x3ccode\x3esplit\x3c/code\x3e looks for 0 or more spaces in a string and returns the first 3 splits that it finds.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3evar myString \x3d \x26quot;Hello World. How are you doing?\x26quot;;\nvar splits \x3d myString.split(\x26quot; \x26quot;, 3);\nprint(splits);\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eThis script displays the following:\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cpre class \x3d "eval"\x3eHello,World.,How\n\x3c/pre\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_9"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Example:_Capturing_parentheses"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch4 class \x3d "editable"\x3eExample: Capturing parentheses\x3c/h4\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eIf \x3ccode\x3eseparator\x3c/code\x3e contains capturing parentheses, matched results are returned in the array.\x3c/p\x3e\n\r\n          \x3cpre name \x3d "code" class \x3d "js"\x3evar myString \x3d \x26quot;Hello 1 word. Sentence number 2.\x26quot;;\nvar splits \x3d myString.split(/(\\d)/);\nprint(splits);\x3c/pre\x3e\r\n        \n\x3cp\x3eThis script displays the following:\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cpre class \x3d "eval"\x3eHello ,1, word. Sentence number ,2, .\n\x3c/pre\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e\x3c/div\x3e',
