'\x3cdiv id \x3d "section_4"\x3e\x3cspan id \x3d "Description"\x3e\x3c/span\x3e\x3ch3 class \x3d "editable"\x3e Description \x3c/h3\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eThe \x3ccode\x3eatan2\x3c/code\x3e method returns a numeric value between -pi and pi representing the angle theta of an (x,y) point. This is the counterclockwise angle, measured in radians, between the positive X axis, and the point (\x3ccode\x3ex,y\x3c/code\x3e). Note that the arguments to this function pass the y-coordinate first and the x-coordinate second.\n\x3c/p\x3e\x3cp\x3e\x3ccode\x3eatan2\x3c/code\x3e is passed separate \x3ccode\x3ex\x3c/code\x3e and \x3ccode\x3ey\x3c/code\x3e arguments, and \x3ccode\x3eatan\x3c/code\x3e is passed the ratio of those two arguments.\n\x3c/p\x3e\x3cp\x3eBecause \x3ccode\x3eatan2\x3c/code\x3e is a static method of \x3ccode\x3eMath\x3c/code\x3e, you always use it as \x3ccode\x3eMath.atan2()\x3c/code\x3e, rather than as a method of a \x3ccode\x3eMath\x3c/code\x3e object you created.\n\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3c/div\x3e',
